03:54.859 --> 03:57.528
♪ I'll be something
Beyond compare ♪

03:57.612 --> 03:58.905
♪ I'll be noticed ♪

03:58.988 --> 04:01.157
♪ Because I'll wear a smile ♪

04:01.241 --> 04:07.330
♪ And a ribbon in my hair ♪

04:10.041 --> 04:12.377
♪ (SONG CONCLUDES) ♪

04:13.294 --> 04:14.712
(SNEAKERS SQUEAKING)

04:14.796 --> 04:16.380
RONNIE GROGAN:
Maybe it's a Dracula thing.

04:16.464 --> 04:19.968
You know, like in the movie,
how we can't see his reflection?

04:20.009 --> 04:21.261
But we did see him.

04:21.344 --> 04:23.263
It could have killed us,
but it didn't.

04:24.138 --> 04:26.266
It's like it's messing with us.

04:26.349 --> 04:27.642
The first thing I'd do
is find out

04:27.684 --> 04:30.019
if there's a history of stuff
like this happening in Derry.

04:30.061 --> 04:32.855
Lilly, your mom
grew up here, right?

04:33.439 --> 04:34.440
Yeah.

04:34.524 --> 04:36.526
She ever mention
anything strange?

04:36.567 --> 04:38.403
No, and if I ask her about it,

04:38.486 --> 04:39.988
she'll send me right back
to Juniper Hill.

04:40.029 --> 04:42.448
-(SHOUTS) But you heard what--
-(SHUSHES)

04:42.532 --> 04:44.784
You heard what Bowers said.

04:44.867 --> 04:46.536
They're gonna transfer my dad
to Shawshank.

04:46.577 --> 04:48.037
You don't come back
from that place.

04:48.079 --> 04:50.373
-Please, I'm just asking--
-No adult's ever gonna believe

04:50.456 --> 04:51.541
what we saw.

04:52.125 --> 04:53.209
I wouldn't.

04:53.251 --> 04:55.378
♪ (INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

04:56.045 --> 04:57.714
Wait.

04:57.797 --> 05:00.883
-I know someone who might.
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

05:00.925 --> 05:02.593
INGRID: I haven't thought
about it in years,

05:02.677 --> 05:04.053
but now that you mention it,

05:04.137 --> 05:06.556
I do remember some kids
going missing in the '30s.

05:06.597 --> 05:07.557
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

05:07.640 --> 05:09.309
Quite a few, actually.

05:09.392 --> 05:10.560
Really?

05:10.601 --> 05:11.853
Well, it was the depression,

05:11.894 --> 05:14.063
and a lot of families
were starving, and some kids,

05:14.147 --> 05:15.940
they just disappeared overnight.

05:16.024 --> 05:17.734
They probably ran away looking
for something better

05:17.775 --> 05:19.902
or trying to relieve
their families of the burden.

05:19.986 --> 05:21.321
They were tough times.

05:21.404 --> 05:23.114
♪ (GENTLE MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS) ♪

05:23.197 --> 05:24.615
But nothing like...

05:24.699 --> 05:27.535
What you're describing?
Oh no, dear. (CHUCKLES)

05:27.577 --> 05:29.078
No, nothing like that.

05:31.497 --> 05:32.874
But don't let that stop you

05:32.915 --> 05:35.084
from trying to figure out
what's happening.

05:36.002 --> 05:37.879
My father always said to me

05:37.920 --> 05:39.589
that with good friends
at your side,

05:39.630 --> 05:40.965
anything's possible.

05:42.091 --> 05:44.427
And it sounds like
you have those.

05:49.349 --> 05:51.351
♪ ("BASIN STREET BLUES"
BY THE MILLS BROTHERS PLAYING) ♪

05:51.433 --> 05:53.478
♪ Oh, Basin Street ♪

05:54.395 --> 05:56.189
♪ Is the street ♪

05:57.440 --> 05:59.776
-♪ Where all ♪
-(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

05:59.859 --> 06:02.528
♪ The elite meet ♪

06:03.613 --> 06:06.032
♪ In New Orleans ♪

06:06.115 --> 06:09.994
♪ The land of dreams
You'll never know... ♪

06:10.078 --> 06:12.663
Hello. Well, this is a surprise.

06:12.747 --> 06:15.541
Thought I'd save you the trouble
of wrestling it home yourself.

06:16.334 --> 06:18.544
Oh, you didn't have to do that.

06:18.628 --> 06:20.338
Just happy it found a good home.

06:20.421 --> 06:22.924
I'm brewing coffee,
if you're in the mood.

06:22.965 --> 06:24.509
I will never say no
to a cup of coffee.

06:24.592 --> 06:26.761
-CHARLOTTE HANLON: All right.
-(CHUCKLES)

06:26.803 --> 06:28.638
-CHARLOTTE: Come on in.
-ROSE: Thank you.

06:28.679 --> 06:30.181
(DOOR CLOSING)

06:30.264 --> 06:32.475
♪ ("WHEN IT'S SLEEPY TIME
DOWN SOUTH"
BY BILLIE HOLIDAY PLAYING) ♪

06:32.558 --> 06:34.977
So, your folks are from
around these parts originally?

06:35.061 --> 06:37.897
My ancestors settled
in the valley here,

06:37.980 --> 06:40.650
but our homelands
were much bigger back then.

06:40.733 --> 06:42.527
-CHARLOTTE: Hmm.
-We would follow the elk herds

06:42.610 --> 06:44.779
all the way into Nova Scotia
and back.

06:45.696 --> 06:48.324
That was before
Manifest Destiny, of course.

06:48.366 --> 06:50.326
I've never been
to Canada myself.

06:50.368 --> 06:52.036
-ROSE: No?
-Mm-mm.

06:53.579 --> 06:56.332
I still have cousins up there,
north of the border.

06:56.374 --> 06:59.168
Well, what they call
a border anyway.

06:59.252 --> 07:01.796
(CHUCKLES) To us,
it's just a line on a map.

07:02.672 --> 07:03.714
Hmm.

07:06.217 --> 07:08.678
So, how is
your husband adjusting?

07:08.719 --> 07:10.012
I suppose
they're keeping him busy

07:10.096 --> 07:11.222
working on that new pipeline.

07:11.305 --> 07:12.515
Oh, Leroy's a pilot.

07:12.557 --> 07:15.101
I doubt he's got anything
to do with that.

07:15.184 --> 07:17.520
Not that he'd tell me
if he did, but...

07:17.562 --> 07:18.688
No?

07:18.771 --> 07:20.523
Every time I ask about his day,

07:20.606 --> 07:24.193
it's national security this,
and classified that.

07:24.235 --> 07:26.988
Man's got more secrets
than King Tut's tomb.

07:29.449 --> 07:31.159
That sounds a little lonely.

07:31.200 --> 07:32.869
Oh, I knew
what I was signing up for

07:32.909 --> 07:34.704
when I married a flyboy.

07:34.745 --> 07:37.165
He doesn't question orders.
I question everything.

07:37.206 --> 07:39.000
-(CHUCKLES)
-That's the dance.

07:39.041 --> 07:40.501
(CHUCKLES)

07:44.005 --> 07:45.339
May I ask you something?

07:45.923 --> 07:47.049
ROSE: Of course.

07:48.885 --> 07:50.386
This...

07:50.470 --> 07:53.931
business with the theater,
the missing kids...

07:56.642 --> 07:58.436
It's a terrible thing.

07:58.519 --> 08:00.438
Do I need to be concerned?

08:01.189 --> 08:03.566
♪ (UNSETTLING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

08:04.692 --> 08:06.944
Derry is a beautiful place,

08:07.945 --> 08:09.655
but things do happen
from time to time.

08:12.283 --> 08:15.077
Never a bad idea to keep
the people you love close.

08:16.996 --> 08:18.331
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪
-(CUP CLINKING)

08:18.414 --> 08:19.749
ROSE: Tell you what.

08:19.790 --> 08:23.044
If you need anything, to talk...

08:23.085 --> 08:24.420
(PEN CLICKS)

08:24.462 --> 08:26.464
-...a friend...
-(PEN SCRIBBLING)

08:26.547 --> 08:27.548
(PEN CLICKS)

08:28.966 --> 08:29.967
...call me.

08:30.051 --> 08:31.511
♪ ("WHAT'D I SAY"
BY RAY CHARLES PLAYING) ♪

08:31.594 --> 08:33.095
♪ Hey, mama
Don't you treat me wrong ♪

08:33.136 --> 08:36.682
♪ Come and love your daddy
All night long, all right now ♪

08:38.267 --> 08:41.895
♪ Hey, hey, all right ♪

08:44.148 --> 08:45.775
(LAUGHS)

08:46.901 --> 08:49.529
♪ See the girl
With the diamond ring ♪

08:49.612 --> 08:51.614
♪ She knows
How to shake that thing ♪

08:51.656 --> 08:53.824
♪ All right, now, now, now ♪

08:54.408 --> 08:55.910
♪ Hey, hey ♪

08:56.953 --> 08:58.412
♪ Hey, hey ♪

09:01.916 --> 09:03.626
-JACOBS: Here we go.
-♪ (SONG FADES) ♪

09:03.668 --> 09:05.336
-JACOBS: This is it.
-JAX: Hallorann!

09:05.419 --> 09:07.380
-REGGIE DAVIS: Let's go!
-Y'all seen this sh-- (SPITS)

09:07.463 --> 09:09.465
-Aw, hell no.
-JAX: (CHUCKLES) I saw that.

09:09.507 --> 09:11.801
Yo, hold on. Let me find
the light up in here.

09:11.884 --> 09:13.719
-Oh, I got it. Hold up.
-REGGIE: Hit the lights.

09:13.803 --> 09:15.346
-JAX: Hey, hey.
-REGGIE: There you go. You...

09:15.429 --> 09:17.014
-JAX: Okay.
-REGGIE: You did it. You did it.

09:17.098 --> 09:18.140
(WHISPERS) Damn.

09:18.224 --> 09:20.518
Hey, ain't it a little far
from base?

09:21.143 --> 09:22.478
REGGIE: That's good.

09:22.520 --> 09:24.480
Mean there's no one
to hassle us.

09:24.564 --> 09:27.775
-You sure it's ours?
-Colonel said we could use it.

09:27.817 --> 09:29.110
Right, right.

09:29.151 --> 09:30.861
And no one else comes here?

09:30.945 --> 09:33.573
Boy, do you know
what "decommissioned" means?

09:33.656 --> 09:34.991
-JAX: No.
-It was all storage out here.

09:35.074 --> 09:36.158
Anything they needed,

09:36.200 --> 09:38.286
they cleared out
a long time ago.

09:38.327 --> 09:39.870
JACOBS: Come on now.
Look at this.

09:39.954 --> 09:42.498
-DICK HALLORANN: What?
-It's a damn mess.

09:42.582 --> 09:45.126
HALLORANN: Yeah.
But the important thing is,

09:45.167 --> 09:46.168
it's got potential.

09:46.627 --> 09:48.087
Oh, hell no.

09:48.170 --> 09:51.674
No, look. You put the bar here,
put the Hi-Fi there.

09:51.716 --> 09:54.176
-(DOOR CREAKS)
-Hey.

09:54.260 --> 09:56.262
Hey, hey, Hallorann.
Maybe you could get, like, a--

09:56.345 --> 09:58.139
a grill or a hot plate
or something, you know?

09:58.180 --> 09:59.348
We could turn this
into a kitchen!

09:59.390 --> 10:01.601
-REGGIE: Ooh!
-Throw a little chow down
for the fellas.

10:01.684 --> 10:02.727
HALLORANN: And their dates.

10:02.810 --> 10:04.228
-(JAX CHUCKLES)
-You can't do that on base.

10:04.312 --> 10:05.688
-JAX: Whoo!
-(AIRMEN CHUCKLE)

10:05.730 --> 10:08.816
Can't do nothing here neither
till we clean this motherfucker.

10:08.858 --> 10:11.986
Come on. Y'all laughing like
we don't gotta clean this shit.

10:12.028 --> 10:13.946
-Damn.
-Let's clean this up, gentlemen.

10:14.030 --> 10:16.032
-REGGIE: Yes, sir.
-(BOTTLES CLINKING)

10:16.073 --> 10:18.075
JACOBS:
Can y'all help me with this?
It's heavy as hell.

10:18.159 --> 10:19.493
REGGIE: Come on, bro.
Maybe we can use

10:19.535 --> 10:20.786
a couple of these things
around here.

10:20.870 --> 10:22.705
-♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
-JACOBS: It's all damn broken.

10:22.788 --> 10:23.706
JAX: There's food here.

10:23.789 --> 10:24.915
JACOBS:
There's food here? Shit.

10:24.999 --> 10:27.001
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-(SCHOOL BELL RINGING)

10:27.043 --> 10:28.878
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

10:30.004 --> 10:31.547
NARRATOR: (OVER SPEAKER)
There is a bright flash,

10:31.631 --> 10:34.800
brighter than the sun.
It could knock you down hard,

10:34.884 --> 10:37.553
or throw you against a tree
or a wall.

10:37.595 --> 10:39.805
-It is such a big explosion...
-(EXPLOSION)

10:39.889 --> 10:42.892
...it can smash in buildings,
and knock signboards over,

10:42.975 --> 10:44.977
and break windows all over town.

10:45.061 --> 10:48.022
But if you duck
and cover like Bert...

10:48.064 --> 10:50.066
-(SIREN BLARING OVER SPEAKER)
-...you'll be much safer.

10:50.149 --> 10:52.151
The atomic bomb flash
could burn you

10:52.234 --> 10:54.236
worse than a terrible sunburn,

10:54.278 --> 10:56.447
-especially where
you're not covered.
-♪ (INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

10:56.530 --> 10:58.491
NARRATOR: Now, you and I
don't have shells

10:58.574 --> 11:00.242
to crawl into
like Bert the Turtle,

11:00.284 --> 11:03.162
so we have to cover up
in our own way.

11:03.245 --> 11:06.957
First, you duck,
and then you cover.

11:07.041 --> 11:08.209
And very tightly,

11:08.250 --> 11:11.253
you cover the back
of your neck and your face.

11:11.337 --> 11:13.631
Duck and cover
underneath a table...

11:13.714 --> 11:16.467
♪ (INTRIGUING MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

11:26.769 --> 11:28.771
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

11:45.037 --> 11:47.623
-(DOOR OPENING)
-Hmm, looking for these?

11:47.707 --> 11:50.209
♪ (UNSETTLING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

11:50.292 --> 11:52.461
CHARLOTTE: I was tidying up,
and I found these stuffed

11:52.503 --> 11:54.755
in an envelope
in the back of that drawer.

11:55.923 --> 11:57.425
What's going on, Will?

11:57.466 --> 12:00.010
-(HESITATES) I was--
-CHARLOTTE: And don't lie to me.

12:03.389 --> 12:05.433
Ronnie is my friend.

12:05.474 --> 12:07.852
She swears her dad didn't do it,
and I believe her,

12:07.935 --> 12:09.687
but the police don't
because he works at the theater.

12:09.770 --> 12:11.772
Yeah, I know, baby.

12:14.567 --> 12:15.609
So...

12:17.069 --> 12:19.321
Me and some other kids, we...

12:19.363 --> 12:21.824
met up to try to figure out
how to help her when...

12:24.326 --> 12:25.369
When what?

12:28.664 --> 12:30.332
-What happened?
-(SNIFFLES)

12:31.959 --> 12:33.961
It was dark. (SNIFFLES)

12:34.003 --> 12:36.338
And someone came after us.

12:37.423 --> 12:39.842
(SNIFFLES)
We were scared and we ran,

12:39.925 --> 12:41.719
but Ronnie had a camera
and she was trying--

12:41.802 --> 12:43.137
trying to get
some pictures and...

12:43.179 --> 12:45.181
(GASPS, SOBS)

12:48.184 --> 12:52.104
-Okay, baby. (SHUSHES)
-(WILL HANLON SOBS)

12:52.188 --> 12:53.814
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

12:53.856 --> 12:54.940
All right,
no more running around

12:55.024 --> 12:56.484
till I find out
what's going on around here.

12:56.525 --> 12:58.360
-What?
-School and back, and that's it.

12:58.444 --> 13:00.029
-Mom.
-Not another word.

13:00.112 --> 13:03.032
Your daddy finds out
you've been running around
wild at night,

13:03.115 --> 13:04.992
you're gonna get
a worse punishment than that.

13:06.410 --> 13:08.537
-(SNIFFLES)
-We'll keep it between us...

13:09.246 --> 13:10.706
this time.

13:14.710 --> 13:16.921
(INSECTS CHIRPING)

13:27.097 --> 13:28.724
How was your first week
at school?

13:29.683 --> 13:31.602
-Fine.
-LEROY HANLON: Fine?

13:32.228 --> 13:34.021
Give me some details.

13:34.063 --> 13:36.857
♪ (SOFT SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC
PLAYING) ♪

13:37.691 --> 13:39.318
Go on, baby. Tell him.

13:43.364 --> 13:44.824
Oh, for goodness' sake.

13:45.783 --> 13:48.327
-There is a girl.
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

13:48.410 --> 13:50.788
-Mom.
-Oh. (CHUCKLES) It's okay.

13:50.871 --> 13:52.122
Don't embarrass the boy, Char.

13:53.499 --> 13:55.209
Can I be excused?

13:55.251 --> 13:57.878
-You haven't even had dessert.
-I have homework.

13:59.713 --> 14:01.674
All right. Go on.

14:09.139 --> 14:10.432
So, the girl is...

14:11.433 --> 14:12.434
I mean, is she...

14:14.478 --> 14:17.565
(BOTH LAUGH)

14:18.148 --> 14:19.149
LEROY: You know.

14:19.692 --> 14:22.444
(LAUGHS)

14:22.486 --> 14:25.114
-Are you working this weekend?
-Oh, um...

14:26.115 --> 14:27.867
I don't know.
I'm just waiting on a call.

14:27.950 --> 14:29.076
Hmm.

14:30.119 --> 14:31.745
Well, I was thinking,

14:31.787 --> 14:34.039
if you're free,
y'all two could do something.

14:35.415 --> 14:37.001
Been so busy since we got here.

14:37.084 --> 14:39.628
Could be good to get him
out of his head for a change.

14:42.339 --> 14:43.340
Yeah.

14:44.383 --> 14:46.260
-Maybe.
-Yeah?

14:47.136 --> 14:48.971
What are you thinking?

14:49.013 --> 14:51.807
-(FOOTSTEPS DEPARTING)
-♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

14:51.849 --> 14:54.393
(CUTLERY CLINKING)

14:54.476 --> 14:59.481
-♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪
-(BIRDS SQUAWKING, CHIRPING)

15:10.034 --> 15:11.785
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

15:11.827 --> 15:12.995
Nice.

15:13.078 --> 15:14.663
(BIRDS CALLING)

15:14.705 --> 15:16.165
-Dad?
-Hmm?

15:16.957 --> 15:18.375
How long do we have to do this?

15:21.045 --> 15:24.882
Have to? (CHUCKLES)
I'm having the time of my life.

15:24.965 --> 15:26.634
Spending time in nature
with my boy,

15:26.675 --> 15:28.135
like I used to with my pops.

15:30.054 --> 15:31.347
It doesn't get better than this.

15:34.516 --> 15:36.310
Tell me about
this new girlfriend of yours.

15:38.145 --> 15:39.313
She's not my girlfriend.

15:39.355 --> 15:41.941
(LEROY GRUNTS
AND SNICKERS PLAYFULLY)

15:42.024 --> 15:43.067
(WILL CHUCKLES)

15:43.859 --> 15:46.487
Not yet? The year is young.

15:46.528 --> 15:47.863
(GIGGLES)

15:47.905 --> 15:49.114
(PLAYFULLY) Ooh.

15:49.198 --> 15:51.325
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

15:51.367 --> 15:54.203
-The year's young, my friend.
-(REEL RATTLING)

15:54.244 --> 15:55.537
-I caught something.
-LEROY: What?

15:55.621 --> 15:57.748
-I got something. (GRUNTS)
-Oh, oh, oh.

15:57.831 --> 15:59.540
Okay, son, relax, relax.
Don't force it.

15:59.625 --> 16:02.002
Just reel it in, uh,
a little bit at a time.

16:02.044 --> 16:03.796
-Come on, easy. Keep it going.
-I'm doing it, Dad.

16:03.879 --> 16:05.339
Keep it going.
You got it. Stay with it.

16:05.381 --> 16:07.132
You gotta stay with him.
There it is.

16:07.216 --> 16:08.884
-(LINE SNAPPING)
-LEROY: Ah! Damn it.

16:08.968 --> 16:11.220
-(BOTH CHUCKLE)
-I got it.

16:11.303 --> 16:14.098
You had it. That's--
He's-- he's gone.

16:14.181 --> 16:15.891
Wind it back.
At least we know they're biting.

16:17.101 --> 16:19.687
Ah. Oh. Hold on, hold on.
Your fly came off.

16:20.479 --> 16:21.939
Yeah, so...

16:23.148 --> 16:24.149
-Watch my line?
-Mm. Mm-hmm.

16:24.233 --> 16:25.567
LEROY: I left the spares
in the car.

16:28.070 --> 16:29.238
(CLEARS THROAT)

16:45.129 --> 16:47.339
(BIRDS CALLING)

16:47.965 --> 16:49.967
♪ (SERENE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

16:50.050 --> 16:51.760
(LEAVES RUSTLING)

16:53.887 --> 16:56.098
(WATER BURBLING)

17:10.738 --> 17:12.698
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

17:19.079 --> 17:20.497
♪ (SCREECHING MUSIC STING) ♪

17:20.580 --> 17:23.291
-(MUFFLED SCREAM)
-♪ (INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

17:24.835 --> 17:26.462
(MUFFLED SCREAM)

17:27.253 --> 17:30.924
(IN HOARSE VOICE)
You'll burn too!

17:30.966 --> 17:32.801
(MUFFLED SCREAM)

17:32.885 --> 17:34.136
Will.

17:38.140 --> 17:39.975
WILL: (SHRIEKING) Dad! Help!

17:40.017 --> 17:41.518
(MUFFLED SCREAM)

17:42.561 --> 17:44.646
-WILL: Dad! Help!
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

17:44.688 --> 17:47.274
Help! Daddy! Help!

17:47.858 --> 17:50.611
(GASPS, COUGHS)

17:50.652 --> 17:52.863
It pulled me under.
It came up out of the water!

17:52.946 --> 17:55.157
What? Son, what is it?
Breathe. Breathe. What did?

17:55.240 --> 17:57.618
(GASPING) It was you.

17:57.659 --> 17:59.745
(HESITATES) You were all burnt
like that picture of you

17:59.828 --> 18:01.497
after the war when you went down
in that plane!

18:01.538 --> 18:03.248
Son, you gotta relax.
You're not making any sense.

18:03.332 --> 18:04.792
-It's the truth!
-Calm down!

18:07.002 --> 18:09.338
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

18:09.379 --> 18:10.672
LEROY: Son, what the hell?

18:12.049 --> 18:15.219
There's something here...
in Derry.

18:15.302 --> 18:17.387
Something bad.
(BREATHES SHAKILY)

18:18.806 --> 18:20.182
(WHIMPERS, SNIFFLES)

18:20.265 --> 18:23.852
♪ (EERIE DISCORDANT
MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

18:25.020 --> 18:30.734
♪ (HAUNTING MUSIC STING) ♪

18:33.403 --> 18:34.696
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

18:34.738 --> 18:36.657
REPORTER: (OVER RADIO)
Reports suggest
that Soviet shipments

18:36.698 --> 18:38.117
that recently arrived
in Cuban ports

18:38.200 --> 18:39.701
may contain military equipment,

18:39.743 --> 18:41.370
including
surface-to-air missiles.

18:41.453 --> 18:43.705
If confirmed, sources say
it would mark a significant...

18:43.747 --> 18:45.165
(BANGING ON DOOR)

18:47.543 --> 18:49.878
KIRN: Chief, you got a visitor.

18:49.962 --> 18:52.381
(REPORTER CONTINUES
SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

18:54.967 --> 18:56.385
(CLINT SIGHS)

18:56.468 --> 18:58.804
No details, no description.

18:58.887 --> 19:00.264
That's not a lot to go on.

19:00.347 --> 19:02.641
They're kids.
They got scared and ran.

19:02.724 --> 19:03.934
CLINT: All right.
We'll look into it.

19:04.017 --> 19:05.477
Is there anything else, Mrs...

19:05.561 --> 19:06.854
Hanlon.

19:06.895 --> 19:08.814
Uh, I don't mean
to be presumptuous,

19:08.897 --> 19:10.732
Chief Bowers,
but if there is someone

19:10.816 --> 19:13.152
out there
still accosting children,

19:13.235 --> 19:16.697
isn't it a possibility you have
an innocent man in your jail?

19:16.738 --> 19:19.408
You're talking
about Hank Grogan? Not a chance.

19:19.449 --> 19:21.660
Not a chance. We questioned him,
we caught him in a lie.

19:21.743 --> 19:23.537
-The man has no alibi.
-Mm.

19:24.580 --> 19:27.124
Has he been able
to consult an attorney?

19:29.001 --> 19:31.170
Mrs. Hanlon,
this isn't the South.

19:31.253 --> 19:33.422
He and his family
have had regular contact

19:33.463 --> 19:35.507
with the public defender's
office.

19:35.591 --> 19:36.842
I didn't mean
to offend you, sir.

19:36.925 --> 19:37.926
I'm sorry.

19:38.844 --> 19:40.888
You can imagine
where I come from,

19:40.929 --> 19:42.097
what I'm used to.

19:46.476 --> 19:48.270
May I speak with him, please?

19:48.353 --> 19:50.939
You're neither counsel
nor family, so no.

19:51.023 --> 19:52.441
Now, if you'll excuse me...

19:53.525 --> 19:56.445
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

19:56.528 --> 19:59.364
(CLEARS THROAT)
Thank you for your time.

19:59.448 --> 20:00.699
CLINT: Mm-hmm.

20:04.912 --> 20:07.623
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

20:08.790 --> 20:11.126
(FOOTSTEPS DEPARTING)

20:15.631 --> 20:17.966
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC
CONTINUES) ♪

20:27.100 --> 20:29.228
"Grogan." Grogan.

20:33.148 --> 20:34.858
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

20:34.942 --> 20:37.486
♪ (BLUES MUSIC
PLAYING OVER RADIO) ♪

20:37.527 --> 20:39.696
LOUELLA GROGAN:
I don't understand, Miss...

20:39.780 --> 20:43.825
Missus. Hanlon.
Call me Charlotte.

20:43.867 --> 20:46.954
My boy, Will, is a friend
of your granddaughter's.

20:46.995 --> 20:48.997
He told me the situation
with your son,

20:49.039 --> 20:51.667
and I just thought I'd check in.

20:51.708 --> 20:53.794
-You a lawyer?
-CHARLOTTE: No, ma'am,

20:53.835 --> 20:56.630
but I was active
in the movement down south.

20:56.672 --> 20:58.632
Did my bit helping
other colored folks

20:58.674 --> 21:01.510
who got forced
into false confessions.

21:01.551 --> 21:03.095
If that's the case
with your son,

21:03.178 --> 21:05.055
I'd like to see
if I could help him too.

21:05.138 --> 21:06.390
That's kind of you,

21:06.473 --> 21:08.475
but I don't see
as it'll do much good.

21:09.268 --> 21:12.020
I thought he was in his room.

21:12.104 --> 21:14.815
Turns out someone saw him
out walking, so...

21:14.856 --> 21:16.191
CHARLOTTE: Hmm.

21:16.275 --> 21:18.068
Doesn't mean he hurt anybody.

21:18.151 --> 21:20.946
Of course not.
My Hank wouldn't hurt a fly.

21:21.655 --> 21:23.573
Especially not no kids.

21:23.657 --> 21:26.410
So, if he wasn't at the theater,
and he wasn't home,

21:27.119 --> 21:28.537
where else could he have been?

21:28.620 --> 21:29.830
♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

21:29.871 --> 21:32.332
The only one who knows
where my son was that night,

21:32.374 --> 21:33.667
other than himself,

21:34.793 --> 21:35.794
is God.

21:37.212 --> 21:39.006
And neither one
of them's talking.

21:43.427 --> 21:44.469
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

21:44.553 --> 21:45.679
(LAMP RATTLES)

21:45.721 --> 21:46.930
AIRMAN: Hey.

21:47.014 --> 21:48.557
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

21:48.598 --> 21:49.891
You're gonna clean it off?

21:49.975 --> 21:52.436
♪ ("YOU CAN'T JUDGE
A BOOK BY THE COVER"
BY BO DIDDLEY PLAYING) ♪

21:52.519 --> 21:56.231
♪ You can't judge an apple
By lookin' at a tree ♪

21:56.315 --> 21:58.900
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)
-♪ You can't judge honey ♪

21:58.984 --> 22:00.902
-♪ By lookin' at the bee ♪
-AIRMAN: There you go, Reg!

22:00.944 --> 22:05.073
♪ You can't judge a daughter
By lookin' at the mother ♪

22:05.115 --> 22:08.827
♪ You can't judge a book
By lookin' at the cover ♪

22:08.910 --> 22:10.912
♪ Oh, can't you see? ♪

22:10.996 --> 22:12.080
Back against the wall. Back--

22:12.164 --> 22:15.083
-(OVERLAPPING CHATTER)
-♪ Oh, you misjudge me ♪

22:15.167 --> 22:17.336
You actually want
the back against the wall, Jax.

22:17.419 --> 22:18.628
JAX: Why aren't you helping?

22:18.712 --> 22:20.505
HALLORANN:
I'm helping right now.

22:20.589 --> 22:22.758
-AIRMAN 1: All right, Hallorann.
-HALLORANN: I can't play.

22:22.799 --> 22:24.301
-(AIRMAN 1 LAUGHS)
-♪ Can't judge a book ♪

22:24.384 --> 22:26.595
-♪ By lookin' at the cover, oh ♪
-AIRMAN 2: Hey! Hallorann!

22:26.678 --> 22:29.931
(AIRMEN LAUGHING, CHEERING)

22:30.015 --> 22:34.686
♪ Whoa, oh! ♪

22:36.730 --> 22:39.483
♪ (SONG TURNS MUFFLED) ♪

22:41.651 --> 22:43.528
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

22:49.284 --> 22:51.119
(SCREECHING WARBLE)

22:51.203 --> 22:53.121
(GROANS)

22:53.205 --> 22:54.289
(VIOLENT GURGLING)

22:56.041 --> 22:58.377
-(LOUD THUD)
-(WARBLING EXPLOSION)

22:58.460 --> 23:00.087
ELDERLY WOMAN:
(IN RASPY VOICE) Dick...

23:00.712 --> 23:01.838
baby.

23:01.922 --> 23:03.673
♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

23:03.757 --> 23:05.801
ELDERLY WOMAN: Mind me now.

23:07.469 --> 23:09.805
You watch yourself, you hear?

23:10.847 --> 23:13.392
Keep that lid on tight.

23:14.434 --> 23:16.395
♪ (MUSIC DISTORTS) ♪

23:19.981 --> 23:21.942
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

23:21.983 --> 23:23.485
-♪ (MUSIC STOPS ABRUPTLY) ♪
-(CAR HORN HONKS)

23:33.954 --> 23:35.580
They said I'd find you here.

23:35.664 --> 23:38.083
(CHUCKLES) Well, here I am.

23:39.668 --> 23:41.002
Hey.

23:41.086 --> 23:42.963
Thanks again
for that home-cooked meal.

23:44.005 --> 23:45.757
The best sleep I had
since I stumbled out

23:45.841 --> 23:46.842
of a cathouse.

23:48.844 --> 23:50.011
Say, you heard anything

23:50.053 --> 23:51.847
from General Shaw
or Colonel Fuller?

23:53.181 --> 23:55.058
Just wondering
when we're going up again.

23:55.142 --> 23:56.768
Oh, no.
That's above my pay grade.

23:56.852 --> 24:00.021
I hear you. But, uh, you know,
that Operation Precept,

24:01.022 --> 24:02.607
Shaw made it sound
like a real priority.

24:04.943 --> 24:06.403
One brother to another,

24:06.486 --> 24:08.196
maybe don't be so eager
to put yourself

24:08.238 --> 24:09.781
in the line of fire on this one.

24:11.700 --> 24:12.909
Now, what are you trying to say?

24:12.993 --> 24:14.786
The Colonel was kind enough

24:14.870 --> 24:16.872
to lend us
this old requisition shed

24:16.955 --> 24:18.707
to use at and for our leisure.

24:18.790 --> 24:20.041
(CHUCKLES)

24:20.125 --> 24:22.002
We're just setting up inside.
You want to help us out?

24:22.043 --> 24:24.880
-LEROY: Hey.
-♪ (UNSETTLING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

24:31.219 --> 24:34.848
Listen, I went fishin' today
with my son,

24:34.890 --> 24:37.434
and when I went back to the car
to get more bait...

24:38.727 --> 24:39.728
something attacked him.

24:40.520 --> 24:43.565
Jesus. I'm sorry. You all right?

24:43.607 --> 24:47.194
When I asked him what,
he said... (BREATHES DEEPLY)

24:47.235 --> 24:49.529
...he said it was me,
all burnt up and charred

24:49.571 --> 24:51.239
like I crawled out
of a plane crash.

24:51.281 --> 24:53.742
And I came up out the water,
tried to pull him under.

24:54.743 --> 24:56.119
You believe him?

24:58.914 --> 25:00.123
The boys got bruises and cuts

25:00.207 --> 25:01.666
like an animal
scratched him all up.

25:04.085 --> 25:05.754
He looked at me,
he said... he said,

25:05.837 --> 25:09.758
"Dad, there's something bad
here in Derry."

25:15.222 --> 25:17.349
Hallorann, what the hell
are we actually looking for?

25:18.141 --> 25:20.268
-(SIGHS)
-LEROY: Huh?

25:20.310 --> 25:22.062
And I know we're trying
to develop some shit.

25:22.103 --> 25:24.439
Russia too.
What, did something go missing?

25:24.481 --> 25:27.442
A machine that fucks
with your head? What is it?

25:29.819 --> 25:31.404
-Answer me!
-I don't know!

25:32.614 --> 25:34.407
I don't know
what the hell it is.

25:34.449 --> 25:36.243
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

25:36.284 --> 25:37.702
Hell, I'm not sure I wanna know.

25:39.538 --> 25:43.041
Look, I do... I do what I'm told
when I'm told, just like you.

25:46.753 --> 25:47.963
I'm sorry about your son.

25:51.591 --> 25:53.093
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

25:54.177 --> 25:55.303
(CLATTER ECHOING)

25:55.387 --> 25:57.138
I used to have nightmares
as a kid about my dad

25:57.222 --> 25:58.974
going down in a plane
like he did in Korea.

25:59.057 --> 26:00.267
♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

26:00.308 --> 26:02.143
WILL: It scared me more
than anything else in the world.

26:02.185 --> 26:04.437
I... (HESITATES)
How did it know that?

26:05.772 --> 26:08.233
It could have killed me
way before my dad got to me.

26:08.316 --> 26:11.069
It can probably kill any one
of us anytime it wants to.

26:14.364 --> 26:15.740
Unless...

26:16.408 --> 26:17.742
Unless what?

26:19.744 --> 26:22.497
What if it doesn't want
to kill us?

26:23.081 --> 26:24.082
Not yet, anyway.

26:24.165 --> 26:27.168
What if it's just trying
to scare us like Lilly said?

26:27.210 --> 26:30.380
Why would it just wanna scare us
when it killed all the others?

26:30.463 --> 26:33.717
We don't actually know
Matty's dead. Not for sure.

26:36.344 --> 26:38.847
But he did tell me
he'd been seeing weird stuff

26:38.888 --> 26:41.349
for a while
before he disappeared.

26:41.391 --> 26:43.643
Phil and Teddy
said the same thing.

26:44.519 --> 26:45.520
Oh man.

26:46.688 --> 26:48.690
-I hate being right.
-What?

26:49.316 --> 26:50.650
Adrenaline.

26:51.818 --> 26:53.278
Cortisol.

26:55.155 --> 26:56.781
They're called
the fear hormones.

26:56.865 --> 26:59.284
When you get scared,
not just you, any mammal,

26:59.367 --> 27:01.536
your adrenal gland secretes them
into your bloodstream,

27:01.620 --> 27:03.747
which some predators
like the taste of.

27:04.706 --> 27:07.250
So, they'll stalk
and scare their prey

27:07.334 --> 27:08.793
until they smell just right.

27:09.377 --> 27:10.837
-Then...
-No, no, no.

27:10.879 --> 27:12.547
You're saying
it wants to eat us?

27:12.589 --> 27:14.424
-It's just a theory.
-It's a horrible theory!

27:14.507 --> 27:16.301
-Well, it fits the facts.
-Okay, let's just,

27:16.384 --> 27:18.345
for the moment,
assume that you're right.

27:18.386 --> 27:20.221
No, I do not wanna assume that.

27:20.305 --> 27:24.934
But if he is,
what are we supposed to do?

27:25.018 --> 27:27.228
I mean, it's not like
we can just stop ourselves

27:27.312 --> 27:28.813
from being scared.

27:31.191 --> 27:32.275
Guys...

27:33.401 --> 27:34.569
what if we could?

27:35.987 --> 27:38.239
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

27:38.323 --> 27:39.574
RONNIE: How'd you get them?

27:39.658 --> 27:41.326
I swiped them
from my mom's compact.

27:42.077 --> 27:43.370
I got one for each of us.

27:44.829 --> 27:45.997
WILL: What does it do?

27:46.081 --> 27:47.916
Whenever she's really nervous
about stuff

27:47.999 --> 27:50.210
like bills or, you know...

27:51.378 --> 27:52.420
me,

27:52.504 --> 27:55.006
she just sticks one
under her tongue.

27:55.090 --> 27:57.258
She says it makes all her fears
and troubles

27:57.300 --> 27:58.927
melt away like magic.

27:58.968 --> 28:00.929
She calls it
"Mommy's Little Helper."

28:01.012 --> 28:03.098
Ah, that sounds pretty good.

28:03.181 --> 28:06.351
So, I guess the second something
weird starts to happen,

28:06.434 --> 28:09.104
-we take it and just--
-And hope for the best.

28:09.187 --> 28:10.438
Yeah. (SIGHS)

28:12.899 --> 28:13.983
(PROJECTOR RATTLING)

28:14.067 --> 28:16.945
MR. MCCRACKEN:
There are almost 20,000 species

28:17.028 --> 28:19.114
-of worms on Earth.
-♪ (QUIRKY MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKER) ♪

28:19.155 --> 28:22.701
Each one unique,
each with its own purpose

28:22.784 --> 28:27.122
in the great swirling apparatus
of our planet's function.

28:27.163 --> 28:29.124
-(POUNDING ON DESK)
-(STUDENT GASPS)

28:29.207 --> 28:31.334
MR. MCCRACKEN: Here we see
the parasitic flatworm,

28:31.418 --> 28:35.672
Leucochloridium paradoxum,
which burrows into the bodies

28:35.755 --> 28:39.134
of land snails,
causing their eyes to swell

28:39.217 --> 28:41.761
and expand
into multicolored stalks,

28:41.803 --> 28:45.640
which subsequently attract
the attention of birds,

28:45.724 --> 28:50.145
who then swoop down
and pluck them out.

28:50.186 --> 28:54.524
Now, the most fascinating aspect
of Leucochloridium paradoxum

28:54.607 --> 28:57.610
is how the parasite not only
alters the snail physically...

28:57.652 --> 28:58.820
MARGE: Hey.

28:58.862 --> 29:01.865
...but also hijacks its brain
and alters its behavior...

29:01.948 --> 29:04.784
I've been thinking about
what a shit I've been lately.

29:07.287 --> 29:08.580
I was wondering if...

29:09.873 --> 29:11.499
I don't know.

29:11.583 --> 29:13.460
Do you wanna go
to lunch with me today?

29:14.002 --> 29:15.837
Just me and you?

29:15.879 --> 29:17.338
(MR. MCCRACKEN
SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY)

29:17.380 --> 29:18.840
I miss you.

29:21.301 --> 29:22.510
That'd be swell.

29:23.636 --> 29:24.637
Peachy.

29:25.597 --> 29:26.639
Can't wait.

29:28.349 --> 29:29.851
MR. MCCRACKEN:
Now, as we consider

29:29.934 --> 29:32.562
-the durability
of parasitic infections...
-♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

29:32.645 --> 29:35.315
...in the animal kingdom,
we should never lose sight

29:35.356 --> 29:38.693
of how easily they can leap
between species.

29:38.735 --> 29:40.320
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪
-(ENGINE REVVING)

29:51.873 --> 29:55.168
♪ (INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

29:56.169 --> 29:57.337
(CAR DOOR OPENS)

30:13.812 --> 30:15.939
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

30:17.148 --> 30:19.108
(SIGHS) Are you family?

30:19.192 --> 30:21.736
No, but I have a letter here
signed by his mother

30:21.778 --> 30:24.155
granting permission
to visit with her son.

30:29.911 --> 30:31.830
Yeah. (INHALES SHARPLY)

30:31.913 --> 30:33.248
You'll have to wait
for the chief.

30:33.289 --> 30:34.666
And when will he be in?

30:35.416 --> 30:36.876
Hard to say.

30:36.918 --> 30:38.419
That's just not good enough.

30:39.170 --> 30:40.255
Listen, lady.

30:41.464 --> 30:44.717
I suggest that you take it
on the arches

30:44.759 --> 30:47.720
before you find yourself
in a cell right next to him.

30:47.762 --> 30:50.682
My name's not Lady,
it's Charlotte Hanlon,

30:50.765 --> 30:52.767
and that may not mean much
to you right now,

30:52.809 --> 30:54.477
but it will when you see
all the scary shit

30:54.561 --> 30:55.895
I can do with a telephone.

30:56.855 --> 30:59.649
-Excuse me?
-No, I don't think I will.

30:59.732 --> 31:03.319
In fact, if you don't let me see
Hank Grogan right now,

31:03.403 --> 31:06.865
by tomorrow morning,
I'll have MLK, JFK, RFK,

31:06.948 --> 31:09.868
and a whole bunch of other FKs
breathing down your neck,

31:09.951 --> 31:11.995
along with a bus full
of Freedom Riders after another

31:12.078 --> 31:13.788
from here to the turnpike

31:13.872 --> 31:15.957
singing "We Shall Overcome"
in the streets

31:15.999 --> 31:17.709
till you have to call
the world's largest cowcatcher

31:17.792 --> 31:19.460
to clear them.

31:19.544 --> 31:21.129
Now, are you gonna let me see
the man?

31:21.796 --> 31:23.631
Or do I need to make a call?

31:25.633 --> 31:27.135
(EXHALES SLOWLY)

31:27.218 --> 31:30.722
♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

31:30.805 --> 31:33.474
HANK GROGAN:
Forgive me, Mrs. Hanlon,
but you don't know my situation.

31:33.558 --> 31:35.101
CHARLOTTE:
I know the cops locked you up

31:35.143 --> 31:37.562
without a shred
of hard evidence.

31:37.645 --> 31:39.314
I spoke with
the public defender's office,

31:39.397 --> 31:40.648
asked some questions.

31:40.690 --> 31:43.026
Turns out they charged you
without a bail hearing,

31:43.109 --> 31:45.069
which is your legal right.

31:45.153 --> 31:46.905
Public defender
ain't say nothing about that.

31:46.988 --> 31:48.823
CHARLOTTE:
We'll worry about him later.

31:48.907 --> 31:50.617
Right now,
we need to file papers citing

31:50.658 --> 31:53.161
prejudicial treatment,
show discrimination,

31:53.202 --> 31:56.164
which should be easy
to do in your case.

31:56.247 --> 31:58.583
It'll allow you
to skip bail altogether

31:58.666 --> 32:01.502
and go on house arrest
while you wait for trial.

32:01.586 --> 32:03.838
-House arrest?
-CHARLOTTE: Mm-hmm.

32:03.880 --> 32:05.173
(HESITATES)
So what you saying? You--

32:05.214 --> 32:06.633
I don't gotta go to Shawshank?

32:06.674 --> 32:08.593
The papers take a minute
to process,

32:08.676 --> 32:10.678
and it sounds like they're
bussing you out tomorrow.

32:10.720 --> 32:12.513
So you may have
to spend a few days there,

32:12.597 --> 32:14.766
but the fact of the matter is,

32:14.849 --> 32:16.893
your right to due process
was violated.

32:17.518 --> 32:19.187
Whatever you did...

32:20.355 --> 32:21.481
or didn't do...

32:23.316 --> 32:24.651
you're gonna be going home.

32:26.069 --> 32:27.278
At least for now.

32:28.404 --> 32:30.448
-(BREATHES DEEPLY)
-CHARLOTTE: That's a promise.

32:32.951 --> 32:33.993
Thank you.

32:35.370 --> 32:38.373
But at some point, Mr. Grogan,

32:38.456 --> 32:41.000
you'll have to go on record
with the truth.

32:42.543 --> 32:43.544
HANK: The truth?

32:44.837 --> 32:47.173
The truth is, I ain't do nothing
to those kids.

32:47.215 --> 32:48.758
Told the police about it too!

32:48.841 --> 32:51.135
Doesn't change the fact
that you weren't

32:51.219 --> 32:52.929
where you claimed to be
that night.

32:54.889 --> 32:56.849
-(SIGHS)
-CHARLOTTE:
Where were you, really?

32:56.891 --> 32:58.601
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

33:02.271 --> 33:04.816
You realize that answer
could set you free.

33:08.778 --> 33:11.114
Whatever you were doing
can't possibly compare

33:11.197 --> 33:13.116
to what you're being accused of.

33:18.371 --> 33:20.665
You want your daughter
to go without a father?

33:22.625 --> 33:23.960
You want your mama
to mourn her son--

33:24.043 --> 33:25.878
(YELLS) You think I want that?

33:26.462 --> 33:27.588
You think I want that?

33:27.630 --> 33:28.756
(POUNDS TABLE)

33:29.424 --> 33:30.967
Man, y'all don't understand.

33:32.593 --> 33:33.761
All right.

33:34.637 --> 33:35.763
So, tell me.

33:36.639 --> 33:37.724
Please.

33:38.891 --> 33:40.977
I think you know by now
I'm on your side.

33:41.853 --> 33:44.272
♪ (UNSETTLING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

33:46.315 --> 33:47.608
I, um...

33:51.320 --> 33:52.321
(CLICKS TONGUE)

33:53.072 --> 33:54.198
I was with a woman.

33:56.034 --> 33:57.493
A married woman?

34:00.455 --> 34:01.622
Not just married.

34:05.460 --> 34:06.878
(WHISPERS) A White woman?

34:09.088 --> 34:11.841
It just happened.
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

34:11.924 --> 34:13.176
CHARLOTTE: "It just happened"?

34:18.097 --> 34:20.141
Look, if...
if anybody finds out...

34:21.684 --> 34:23.478
I won't be heading
to no Shawshank.

34:24.437 --> 34:26.313
They'll just find
the nearest tree.

34:26.397 --> 34:28.232
Not to mention what
her husband would do to her.

34:28.315 --> 34:29.358
CHARLOTTE: Mm.

34:30.985 --> 34:33.821
Now, if there's a way out
without anyone getting hurt,

34:34.322 --> 34:35.572
I'll take it.

34:39.034 --> 34:40.286
I... I might...

34:40.328 --> 34:41.996
I might need some help
finding it.

34:46.708 --> 34:48.168
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

34:48.252 --> 34:50.838
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

34:50.922 --> 34:53.341
Sir, we checked the areas
the Indian woman told us

34:53.382 --> 34:54.634
to stay away from.

34:54.675 --> 34:56.969
Either she's telling the truth
or sending us

34:57.011 --> 34:59.388
on a wild goose chase,
but there is nothing there.

35:00.723 --> 35:02.141
Of course there's nothing there.

35:03.309 --> 35:05.103
She's a smart woman.

35:05.186 --> 35:06.896
And now we've confirmed
her suspicions.

35:06.979 --> 35:08.147
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

35:08.189 --> 35:09.440
Believe me, Colonel,
these people take

35:09.524 --> 35:10.983
their obligations
very seriously.

35:11.025 --> 35:12.610
And whatever comes next,
it's not gonna be

35:12.693 --> 35:14.028
a cease and desist letter.

35:14.946 --> 35:16.906
Not that it matters.

35:16.989 --> 35:19.158
Because the cycle
will be over soon,

35:19.200 --> 35:20.535
and the weapon gone
to ground. (SIGHS)

35:20.618 --> 35:22.620
FULLER: Maybe it's time
to begin cleanup, sir.

35:22.703 --> 35:25.873
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

35:43.307 --> 35:45.726
SHAW: How often
are those kids out there
watching the base?

35:45.810 --> 35:47.687
The kids from Indian Marsh?

35:47.728 --> 35:49.397
I don't know,
every couple of days.

35:50.648 --> 35:51.691
Sir, they may be curious,

35:51.732 --> 35:53.651
but they know to stay
on their own side of the fence.

35:54.652 --> 35:56.404
Maybe it's time
we open the gate.

35:57.405 --> 35:58.698
Invite them in.

36:02.160 --> 36:03.870
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
-(BIRDS CHIRPING)

36:03.911 --> 36:06.706
So, how are things
with your new friends?

36:06.747 --> 36:08.082
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

36:08.166 --> 36:09.375
LILLY: What do you mean?

36:09.417 --> 36:11.878
I don't know.
I guess I'm just curious.

36:12.962 --> 36:14.380
What's Ronnie Grogan like?

36:15.882 --> 36:16.883
People talk.

36:18.009 --> 36:19.886
If you invited me to gossip,
I'm not--

36:19.927 --> 36:21.095
Lilly, no.

36:22.221 --> 36:23.514
I just...

36:23.598 --> 36:26.642
I guess I just don't know
how to talk to you anymore.

36:26.726 --> 36:29.729
Everything's changed so much
since you got back from...

36:30.855 --> 36:32.064
you know.

36:33.900 --> 36:36.360
(SIGHS) Look,
we've been best friends

36:36.444 --> 36:37.695
since first grade.

36:38.905 --> 36:42.491
Forget the Pattycakes.
I don't wanna lose you.

36:42.575 --> 36:44.243
Can we just start over?

36:45.328 --> 36:46.579
Please?

36:47.330 --> 36:48.789
I'd like that.

36:49.665 --> 36:51.125
Hey, Marge.

36:53.753 --> 36:54.795
Hey, Lilly.

36:59.008 --> 37:00.801
Oh my gosh.

37:00.843 --> 37:03.721
Did you see the way Tim Flanagan
just looked at you?

37:04.555 --> 37:06.140
You should talk to him.

37:06.224 --> 37:08.309
What? No way.

37:08.392 --> 37:10.436
He's totally sweet on you.

37:11.562 --> 37:13.981
Come on, at least say hi.

37:14.023 --> 37:16.108
After everything you've been
through this year,

37:16.859 --> 37:18.236
you deserve it.

37:20.488 --> 37:22.573
Well, I should at least
freshen up first.

37:26.327 --> 37:27.370
(GIGGLES)

37:28.537 --> 37:30.498
Okay. I'll be right back.

37:32.792 --> 37:35.920
(SIGHS)

37:43.719 --> 37:45.471
Did she go for it?

37:45.513 --> 37:47.848
I think so. She's freshening up.

37:47.890 --> 37:50.601
Good. 'Cause it's all set.

37:50.685 --> 37:52.853
The second she goes over to him,
he's gonna embarrass her

37:52.895 --> 37:54.605
-in front of the whole school.
-(CHUCKLES)

37:54.689 --> 37:55.690
It's gonna be so boss.

37:55.773 --> 37:58.901
(CHUCKLES) Yeah, real boss.

38:00.194 --> 38:01.696
Don't chicken out now, Truman.

38:02.738 --> 38:04.657
Get in there
before she changes her mind.

38:11.205 --> 38:14.458
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

38:16.711 --> 38:17.795
What's the holdup?

38:18.838 --> 38:20.381
LILLY: (SIGHS) I have a zit.

38:21.966 --> 38:24.176
MARGE:
Oh, you can barely see it.

38:24.218 --> 38:26.554
Let me touch you up
before you go back out.

38:26.595 --> 38:28.097
You'll be drop-dead.

38:28.180 --> 38:29.265
Okay.

38:30.182 --> 38:32.143
Let me pee first. I'm nervous.

38:38.858 --> 38:41.485
I can't believe Tim likes me.
(GIGGLES)

38:43.654 --> 38:45.614
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

38:46.282 --> 38:48.534
♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

38:48.576 --> 38:49.827
(SIGHS)

38:59.837 --> 39:00.838
Lills?

39:01.589 --> 39:02.590
LILLY: Yeah?

39:03.132 --> 39:04.550
(BREATHES DEEPLY)

39:07.219 --> 39:08.763
I need to tell you something.

39:09.764 --> 39:10.931
What?

39:11.015 --> 39:14.435
(BREATHES DEEPLY, SNIFFLES)

39:15.436 --> 39:16.479
I, um...

39:17.021 --> 39:19.482
(EXHALES) Well...

39:19.565 --> 39:22.234
(SNIFFLES, BREATHES DEEPLY)

39:23.235 --> 39:25.112
-The truth is...
-(CRACKLING SQUELCH)

39:25.154 --> 39:26.614
-(GROANS)
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

39:26.655 --> 39:29.700
-Marge?
-(MARGE GROANS, SIGHS)

39:30.201 --> 39:31.619
Marge, are you okay?

39:31.660 --> 39:33.913
MARGE: (GROANS) Ow.

39:34.830 --> 39:35.998
(WHISPERS) What?

39:36.916 --> 39:38.584
(MUFFLED CHITTERING)

39:38.626 --> 39:40.836
-♪ (EERIE MUSIC STING) ♪
-(MARGE GROANS, SCREAMS)

39:40.920 --> 39:41.962
Marge, what's wrong?

39:42.046 --> 39:43.839
-(GROANS, SCREAMS)
-(CRACKLING SQUELCH)

39:43.923 --> 39:45.591
-(MARGE SCREAMS)
-(ECHOING RUMBLE)

39:45.633 --> 39:47.051
MARGE: My eyes!

39:47.134 --> 39:49.261
-(BREATHES HEAVILY)
-♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

39:49.303 --> 39:51.222
-(CHITTERING)
-LILLY: Marge!

39:52.139 --> 39:53.432
(EYEBALLS CHITTER)

39:53.474 --> 39:55.476
-(GASPS, SCREAMS)
-♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

39:57.311 --> 39:58.562
-(MARGE SCREAMS)
-Whatever you do,

39:58.646 --> 40:01.023
-just don't look at it, okay?
-MARGE: Somebody help me!

40:01.107 --> 40:02.483
-Close your eyes!
-(PILLBOX RATTLES)

40:03.984 --> 40:06.487
-(DRONING WARBLE)
-(SCREAMS) My eyes!

40:06.529 --> 40:08.948
(SOBS, SCREAMS)

40:09.573 --> 40:10.741
Marge, wait!

40:10.825 --> 40:13.160
♪ (INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

40:13.244 --> 40:16.205
Help! (GROANS)

40:17.248 --> 40:20.584
-(DRONING WARBLE)
-(SCREAMS, GROANS)

40:21.585 --> 40:22.586
(GROANS)

40:22.670 --> 40:25.339
(SCREAMS)

40:25.381 --> 40:28.843
-♪ (MUSIC CALMS) ♪
-(MARGE WAILING IN AGONY)

40:28.926 --> 40:30.886
-(DRONING WARBLE)
-♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

40:31.595 --> 40:32.596
(GASPS)

40:33.848 --> 40:35.266
(PANTS)

40:37.351 --> 40:38.811
(EYEBALLS TRILLING)

40:43.274 --> 40:45.484
(GRUNTS, YELLS)

40:47.194 --> 40:50.030
(GRUNTS, YELLS)

40:50.072 --> 40:51.073
(EYEBALLS CHITTER LOUDLY)

40:51.157 --> 40:52.199
(GROANS)

40:52.283 --> 40:53.576
(EYEBALLS SQUELCHING)

40:54.577 --> 40:58.330
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

40:59.290 --> 41:01.667
(SAW RUMBLING, WHIRRING)

41:03.002 --> 41:05.713
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

41:05.796 --> 41:07.298
-♪ (MUSIC STOPS ABRUPTLY) ♪
-Marge!

41:09.049 --> 41:11.427
-(SCREAMS)
-LILLY: Marge!

41:11.510 --> 41:14.138
-(PANTS, GROANS)
-♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

41:14.221 --> 41:15.723
-Marge, no!
-(MARGE WAILS IN AGONY)

41:15.764 --> 41:18.225
-Marge, stop! No!
-(SCREAMS)

41:18.267 --> 41:20.895
-Stop! Let go!
-(MARGE WAILS IN AGONY)

41:20.936 --> 41:22.271
LILLY: Stop, Marge!

41:22.354 --> 41:25.107
-Marge, stop! (YELPS)
-♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

41:25.191 --> 41:27.568
-No! No! No!
-(MARGE GRUNTS)

41:27.651 --> 41:30.237
-No, Marge, stop!
-(MARGE WAILS)

41:30.279 --> 41:31.489
Let go!

41:32.573 --> 41:34.742
-Let go! Stop!
-♪ (MUSIC CALMS) ♪

41:35.284 --> 41:37.578
(MARGE SOBS)

41:39.538 --> 41:43.417
(SOBS, WAILS)

41:47.004 --> 41:49.590
♪ (MUSIC TURNS EERIE) ♪

41:50.174 --> 41:51.258
LILLY: (HESITATES) No.

41:51.342 --> 41:53.594
(GASPS, HESITATES)
No, I didn't...

41:53.636 --> 41:56.263
(MARGE SOBBING)

41:58.265 --> 41:59.725
(SOBS)

41:59.767 --> 42:01.769
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

42:01.810 --> 42:03.604
-(TOMATO SQUELCHES)
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

42:04.688 --> 42:07.441
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

42:07.483 --> 42:09.443
(FLOORBOARDS CREAKING)

42:10.611 --> 42:12.112
You scared me.

42:12.154 --> 42:13.906
What were you doing
in town today?

42:14.990 --> 42:16.784
What do you mean?

42:16.867 --> 42:19.453
Pauly said he saw you walking
into the police station.

42:19.495 --> 42:21.705
♪ (TENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

42:23.666 --> 42:24.667
I can see the wheels turning,

42:24.750 --> 42:26.418
so why don't you
just tell me, Char?

42:26.460 --> 42:28.629
Same way you tell me
what happens at that base?

42:28.712 --> 42:30.798
That's a security issue.
What is this?

42:30.881 --> 42:32.508
The man that got arrested
at the movie theater?

42:32.591 --> 42:33.842
A Black man who's arrested

42:33.926 --> 42:36.554
for a murder
he swears he didn't commit.

42:36.637 --> 42:39.598
And his daughter
is friends with our son.

42:40.724 --> 42:41.767
His daughter?

42:46.105 --> 42:47.439
Don't be looking for trouble.

42:47.481 --> 42:49.650
There's gonna be trouble
anywhere we go.

42:49.733 --> 42:52.820
That's the country
you swore your life to defend.

42:52.861 --> 42:54.196
I'm just making it
worth defending.

42:54.280 --> 42:57.449
You swore to me
that you wouldn't start up here.

42:57.491 --> 43:00.202
I can't have you getting
arrested again, Char. Not now.

43:01.579 --> 43:04.790
What I'm doing here
is too important.

43:04.832 --> 43:07.001
So, I...
I just need you to trust me.

43:07.084 --> 43:09.295
Just trust me
and don't stir the pot.

43:09.336 --> 43:11.130
Please, just promise me that.

43:12.840 --> 43:13.882
Please.

43:16.135 --> 43:17.970
You won't have
to worry about me.

43:32.318 --> 43:34.403
-(FOOTSTEPS DEPARTING)
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

43:34.486 --> 43:36.739
-(INSECTS CHIRPING)
-(OWL HOOTING)

43:51.420 --> 43:53.922
♪ (SOFT EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

44:05.934 --> 44:10.356
♪ (SCREECHING
OMINOUS MUSIC STING) ♪

44:10.397 --> 44:13.484
♪ (SOFT EERIE MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

44:25.996 --> 44:27.790
-(SIGHS)
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

44:41.053 --> 44:44.098
-(OWL HOOTING)
-♪ (INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

45:10.666 --> 45:12.292
-♪ (SCREECHING MUSIC STING) ♪
-(SCREAMS)

45:12.376 --> 45:15.170
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

45:20.050 --> 45:22.344
LEROY: Hey. What's wrong?
What happened?

45:22.428 --> 45:25.055
I... I couldn't sleep.
I was using the telescope,

45:25.139 --> 45:27.182
and there was somebody
outside staring at me.

45:31.687 --> 45:33.021
CHARLOTTE: What's wrong?

45:34.231 --> 45:36.775
You see what you did?
Someone's watching the house.

45:36.817 --> 45:40.404
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

45:45.117 --> 45:46.368
LEROY: (YELLS) Who's out here?

45:48.620 --> 45:51.081
Show yourself! Huh?

45:51.165 --> 45:53.959
(DOGS BARKING IN DISTANCE)

45:58.839 --> 46:01.467
♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

46:03.093 --> 46:07.055
(PANTS)

46:10.934 --> 46:14.146
-(LEAVES RUSTLING)
-(BOUNCING THUDS)

46:17.399 --> 46:21.028
-♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
-(RUBBER SQUEAKING SOFTLY)

46:33.040 --> 46:34.875
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

46:36.418 --> 46:39.296
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

46:39.379 --> 46:40.964
-♪ (MUSIC STOPS) ♪
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)

46:41.048 --> 46:43.133
Wait, you can't just...

46:47.137 --> 46:48.806
Handle it. Get back to me.

46:49.431 --> 46:51.225
I'm sorry, General.

46:51.308 --> 46:53.018
What the hell
do you have us chasing?

46:54.728 --> 46:57.105
-(EXHALES SOFTLY)
-♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

46:58.607 --> 47:02.152
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC
CONTINUES) ♪

47:13.872 --> 47:16.333
SHAW:
We caught him and his friends
scoping out the base.

47:16.416 --> 47:18.710
Tried to get a peek
over our fence, as it were.

47:21.088 --> 47:23.715
-What's he doing here?
-(DOOR CLOSING)

47:23.757 --> 47:28.095
SHAW: Our young Indian friend,
Taniel is his name,

47:28.136 --> 47:30.722
he knows the location of exactly
what we're looking for.

47:31.598 --> 47:33.517
But he refuses
to answer our questions.

47:34.601 --> 47:38.021
So, Airman Hallorann
is gonna answer them for us.

47:44.486 --> 47:46.196
(OVER INTERCOM)
They're watching over there.

47:50.200 --> 47:51.952
What they want me
to do to you...

47:52.703 --> 47:54.121
it's not gonna be pleasant.

47:55.455 --> 47:58.083
So, why don't you just tell 'em
what they wanna know?

47:58.125 --> 47:59.960
Save us both
a whole lot of pain.

48:05.299 --> 48:06.383
HALLORANN: Yeah.

48:10.637 --> 48:13.140
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

48:15.809 --> 48:17.394
-(SPITS)
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

48:18.812 --> 48:21.440
-♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
-(HALLORANN CHUCKLES)

48:22.190 --> 48:23.567
Oh, Taniel.

48:26.737 --> 48:28.572
God, I'm so sorry about this.

48:34.328 --> 48:38.498
(BREATHES SHAKILY)

48:38.540 --> 48:40.834
(FAINT DRONING WARBLE)

48:40.918 --> 48:44.171
(GRUNTS, BREATHES SHARPLY)

48:46.089 --> 48:49.551
(BREATHES SHAKILY, PANTS)

48:52.971 --> 48:54.222
(GROANS)

48:54.306 --> 48:56.266
-(INHALES SHARPLY)
-(DRONING WARBLE)

48:56.350 --> 48:59.019
-(GROANS)
-♪ (MUSIC TURNS EERIE) ♪

49:01.104 --> 49:02.314
HALLORANN: (MUTTERS) Come on.

49:02.356 --> 49:05.817
(HISSING, DRONING WARBLE)

49:07.027 --> 49:09.821
(HALLORANN BREATHING SHAKILY
OVER INTERCOM)

49:09.863 --> 49:12.240
(WARBLE GROWS LOUDER)

49:13.200 --> 49:14.993
(GROANS)

49:17.412 --> 49:18.538
(TANIEL GROANS)

49:18.580 --> 49:22.084
(DRONING WARBLE CONTINUES)

49:25.796 --> 49:27.214
(GRUNTS)

49:28.507 --> 49:29.549
(TANIEL GRUNTS)

49:31.885 --> 49:35.389
-(GRUNTS, GROANS)
-♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

49:36.139 --> 49:37.349
(GRUNTS)

49:45.315 --> 49:47.859
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

49:47.901 --> 49:48.902
♪ (MUSIC STOPS) ♪

49:48.986 --> 49:51.238
-(SHARP WHOOSH)
-♪ (INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

49:51.321 --> 49:55.200
(SCREAMS)

49:55.909 --> 49:57.536
(ABRUPT SILENCE)

49:59.621 --> 50:00.914
(ECHOING HUM)

50:00.956 --> 50:03.750
(OVERLAPPING VOICES
GIGGLING, CHATTERING)

50:03.792 --> 50:06.253
-♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪
-VOICE: Happy birthday!

50:06.336 --> 50:09.464
VOICES: Happy birthday, Taniel!

50:09.548 --> 50:14.803
(OVERLAPPING VOICES
CHATTERING, ECHOING)

50:20.767 --> 50:22.602
VOICE: (ECHOING)
I need to tell you something.

50:22.644 --> 50:24.646
-(ECHOING RUMBLE)
-(OVERLAPPING CHATTER FADES)

50:24.730 --> 50:26.898
(DOOR CREAKING)

50:35.282 --> 50:37.826
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

50:39.911 --> 50:43.123
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪
-(YOUNG TANIEL IMITATING ROARS)

50:43.206 --> 50:44.291
(IMITATES EXPLOSION)

50:44.332 --> 50:46.251
♪ (PENSIVE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

50:46.293 --> 50:49.379
YOUNG TANIEL: Oh!
"No! He's eating them!"

50:49.463 --> 50:52.340
(IMITATES EXPLOSION, ROAR)

50:52.424 --> 50:54.051
"No!"

50:54.134 --> 50:56.803
"I'll get you for that."
(IMITATES GUNFIRE)

50:56.887 --> 50:58.472
(MUMBLES INDISTINCTLY)

50:58.555 --> 51:00.348
-ROSE: Taniel?
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

51:00.432 --> 51:02.309
-Hi, Auntie.
-Hey.

51:02.392 --> 51:04.936
-What you doing?
-YOUNG TANIEL: Nothing.

51:07.939 --> 51:09.316
(SIGHS)

51:11.234 --> 51:12.527
(IMITATES ROAR)

51:14.529 --> 51:15.530
What is it?

51:18.450 --> 51:20.118
You know the story
about the monster

51:20.160 --> 51:21.495
in the Western Wood?

51:22.537 --> 51:24.331
-The Galloo?
-Mm-hmm.

51:24.372 --> 51:26.249
All the kids know that story.

51:26.333 --> 51:29.836
The elders made us memorize it
when we were, like, seven.

51:29.920 --> 51:31.588
Well, some of our stories...

51:33.215 --> 51:34.883
are meant to teach us lessons.

51:38.095 --> 51:39.971
And some of our stories
are real.

51:40.013 --> 51:42.182
♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

51:44.518 --> 51:48.438
So you're telling me
The Galloo is real?

51:49.940 --> 51:51.024
(ROSE SIGHS)

52:00.826 --> 52:02.077
Tell me the story.

52:02.160 --> 52:05.622
I need to know you remember
how all of this began.

52:07.666 --> 52:08.667
(SIGHS)

52:12.504 --> 52:14.881
Millions of years ago...

52:14.923 --> 52:17.134
Before the time
of the first people,

52:17.217 --> 52:19.302
an evil spirit was cast down

52:19.386 --> 52:21.930
from the darkest part
of the night sky,

52:22.013 --> 52:23.849
bound inside of a falling star.

52:23.890 --> 52:25.725
-♪ (EERIE MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪
-(RUMBLING WHOOSH)

52:25.767 --> 52:27.394
(BOOMING CRASH)

52:29.688 --> 52:32.065
YOUNG TANIEL:
But when the star
struck the Earth,

52:32.149 --> 52:36.403
it broke open,
and the spirit was set free.

52:36.444 --> 52:38.822
It roamed the woods
for many snows

52:38.905 --> 52:40.782
and countless moons...

52:40.866 --> 52:45.245
until the creation
of our first ancestors.

52:47.873 --> 52:51.751
The star that carried
the monster had been its cage,

52:51.793 --> 52:55.422
and the stone it was made from
still held power.

52:56.548 --> 52:59.718
Our wisest took a shard
from that star

52:59.759 --> 53:02.470
and carved a weapon
to protect our people

53:02.554 --> 53:03.972
from the monster.

53:04.055 --> 53:06.808
Which we named "The Galloo."

53:06.892 --> 53:08.602
♪ (MUSIC TURNS OMINOUS) ♪

53:08.685 --> 53:10.478
YOUNG TANIEL:
We kept the dagger close

53:10.562 --> 53:12.814
and stayed away
from the Western Wood.

53:14.149 --> 53:16.651
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪
-YOUNG TANIEL: As years went by,

53:16.735 --> 53:18.987
the legend of The Galloo
was passed down

53:19.905 --> 53:22.073
from generation to generation.

53:22.115 --> 53:24.201
♪ (GROUP SINGING
IN INDIGENOUS LANGUAGE) ♪

53:24.284 --> 53:26.411
YOUNG TANIEL:
We lived in balance
with the monster

53:26.453 --> 53:28.622
by staying outside of its reach

53:28.705 --> 53:30.790
and never hunting
in its territory.

53:30.874 --> 53:32.375
♪ (DRUMS BEATING RHYTHMICALLY) ♪

53:32.459 --> 53:33.960
YOUNG TANIEL: Until one day...

53:34.002 --> 53:36.463
-(HORSES NEIGHING)
-...the settlers arrived.

53:37.631 --> 53:40.842
We warned them of the danger
in the Western Wood,

53:40.926 --> 53:42.552
but they chose to ignore us.

53:42.636 --> 53:44.387
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

53:44.471 --> 53:46.598
-(GUNSHOTS)
-YOUNG TANIEL:
They hunted the woods.

53:46.640 --> 53:48.475
And just as we had warned them,

53:48.558 --> 53:51.937
-they were hunted.
-(CREATURE SCREECHING)

53:51.978 --> 53:53.647
YOUNG TANIEL:
The Galloo fed on them

53:53.688 --> 53:56.233
and grew stronger
and more powerful.

53:56.316 --> 53:57.901
(ECHOING RUMBLE)

53:57.984 --> 54:00.278
YOUNG TANIEL:
The monster would soon be able

54:00.320 --> 54:02.864
to hunt outside
of the Western Wood.

54:02.948 --> 54:04.157
♪ (MUSIC TURNS INTRIGUING) ♪

54:04.241 --> 54:06.993
YOUNG TANIEL: Sesqui,
the village's great war chief,

54:07.035 --> 54:09.371
was called to council
by the clan mothers.

54:09.454 --> 54:11.957
The creature had grown
too powerful.

54:11.998 --> 54:14.584
A single dagger
could no longer protect

54:14.668 --> 54:16.753
all the villages.

54:16.836 --> 54:19.673
To save our people,
the decision was made.

54:19.714 --> 54:22.175
They would have to leave.

54:22.217 --> 54:24.469
But Sesqui's daughter, Necani,

54:24.511 --> 54:26.596
did not want to leave our land.

54:26.680 --> 54:29.349
She believed
there was another path.

54:29.432 --> 54:31.268
She took the dagger

54:31.351 --> 54:33.561
and journeyed past
the great dead wood

54:33.645 --> 54:35.522
with her friends by her side.

54:36.606 --> 54:39.526
Finally arriving
at the Western Wood.

54:39.567 --> 54:42.362
♪ (MUSIC SWELLS) ♪

54:42.445 --> 54:43.905
YOUNG TANIEL:
They entered the woods,

54:43.989 --> 54:46.408
seeking the cave
where The Galloo crashed

54:46.491 --> 54:49.202
to gather more
of the sacred stone.

54:49.244 --> 54:50.578
♪ (TENSE DRUM MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

54:50.662 --> 54:52.205
YOUNG TANIEL:
When Sesqui realized

54:52.247 --> 54:54.708
that her daughter
and the dagger were missing,

54:54.791 --> 54:57.752
she formed a search party
to bring them both back.

54:58.461 --> 55:00.755
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC STING) ♪

55:02.340 --> 55:04.050
YOUNG TANIEL:
But without the dagger,

55:04.134 --> 55:05.218
they had nothing

55:05.260 --> 55:07.178
to protect themselves
from The Galloo.

55:07.220 --> 55:10.140
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

55:12.809 --> 55:14.311
-(TWIGS SNAPPING)
-(GASPS)

55:14.394 --> 55:16.187
-(CREATURE GROWLING)
-♪ (SINISTER MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

55:16.229 --> 55:18.106
YOUNG TANIEL: The monster
showed itself to them.

55:18.189 --> 55:19.399
(GROWLS)

55:19.441 --> 55:21.109
YOUNG TANIEL:
In the shape of the things

55:21.192 --> 55:22.694
they feared the most.

55:22.736 --> 55:24.446
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

55:24.529 --> 55:25.989
(WARRIOR SCREAMS)

55:27.198 --> 55:29.451
YOUNG TANIEL:
It separated the war party.

55:29.534 --> 55:30.910
One by one.

55:32.579 --> 55:34.122
And before she knew it,

55:34.205 --> 55:37.417
Sesqui found herself alone.

55:37.500 --> 55:39.085
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

55:39.127 --> 55:40.503
(TWIG SNAPS)

55:40.587 --> 55:42.005
♪ (SCREECHING MUSIC STING) ♪

55:42.589 --> 55:43.757
(ARROW WHISTLES)

55:44.632 --> 55:46.217
(GROWLS SINISTERLY)

55:46.259 --> 55:49.387
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

55:54.267 --> 55:56.603
-(CREATURE CHITTERS)
-(BONES CRACKLING)

55:56.644 --> 55:58.063
(ROARS)

55:59.939 --> 56:01.691
-(SCREECHES)
-(GRUNTS)

56:01.775 --> 56:05.403
YOUNG TANIEL: Sesqui's only hope
was in her daughter's hands.

56:07.447 --> 56:10.116
♪ (SINISTER CHORAL
MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

56:12.702 --> 56:16.873
(IN HOARSE VOICE)
Prepare to meet thy God!

56:16.956 --> 56:19.709
YOUNG TANIEL:
Even Sesqui, the great warrior,

56:19.793 --> 56:22.462
was no match for The Galloo.

56:22.504 --> 56:24.297
♪ (SINISTER MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

56:24.381 --> 56:26.132
-(CREATURE GROWLS)
-(FLESH BUBBLING)

56:26.174 --> 56:28.093
(BONES CRACKING)

56:28.134 --> 56:29.803
(SHRIEKS)

56:29.844 --> 56:31.304
(SCREAMS)

56:31.388 --> 56:33.556
-(ECHOING SCREAM)
-Mom?

56:34.724 --> 56:36.184
Mom!

56:36.267 --> 56:38.478
-(SESQUI SCREAMS)
-(CREATURE WAILING)

56:38.561 --> 56:41.272
(SCREAMS)

56:41.314 --> 56:42.732
(SESQUI GROANS)

56:43.274 --> 56:46.486
(ROARS)

56:47.028 --> 56:48.029
NECANI: Mom!

56:48.113 --> 56:49.364
Mom, no!

56:49.447 --> 56:50.990
(GROWLS)

56:51.866 --> 56:53.034
(CREATURE SNARLS)

56:53.118 --> 56:54.869
-Mom!
-♪ (MUSIC FADES) ♪

56:54.953 --> 56:55.995
(PANTS) No.

56:56.037 --> 56:57.580
-(SESQUI WHEEZES)
-♪ (SOMBER MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

56:57.664 --> 57:00.166
-(SOBS)
-YOUNG TANIEL:
But it was too late.

57:00.250 --> 57:03.670
Sesqui's spirit
was already slipping away.

57:03.711 --> 57:06.714
♪ (SOMBER MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

57:06.798 --> 57:09.342
YOUNG TANIEL: And she went
to be with the ancestors.

57:09.426 --> 57:11.845
Mom! No! Mom! (SOBS)

57:13.805 --> 57:16.015
(SOBBING) No!

57:16.057 --> 57:22.564
♪ (GROUP SINGING
IN INDIGENOUS LANGUAGE) ♪

57:24.441 --> 57:27.861
♪ (SINGING CONTINUES) ♪

57:27.902 --> 57:31.114
YOUNG TANIEL:
Though Necani's tears
would not stop flowing,

57:31.197 --> 57:33.575
her people were still in danger.

57:33.658 --> 57:35.660
She knew what she had to do.

57:35.702 --> 57:39.122
Fight for them,
just like her mother always had.

57:39.205 --> 57:41.040
So, Necani took the dagger

57:41.124 --> 57:44.627
and braved the Western Wood
one last time.

57:44.711 --> 57:46.379
♪ (INTRIGUING MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

57:47.380 --> 57:49.257
♪ (MUSIC SWELLS) ♪

57:49.340 --> 57:51.342
YOUNG TANIEL:
They found the cave.

57:53.052 --> 57:54.387
And broke off shards

57:54.429 --> 57:56.890
of the ancient star
The Galloo had arrived in.

57:59.684 --> 58:01.519
-(CHISEL CLINKING)
-♪ (MUSIC CALMS) ♪

58:01.561 --> 58:03.146
YOUNG TANIEL: A plan was formed.

58:04.564 --> 58:06.191
Not to kill it,

58:06.232 --> 58:07.650
but to cage it.

58:07.734 --> 58:11.905
-(THUNDER CRASHING)
-♪ (MUSIC TURNS DARING) ♪

58:13.907 --> 58:16.743
YOUNG TANIEL:
They would use the shards
of its old bindings,

58:16.784 --> 58:19.037
the only thing
The Galloo feared,

58:19.078 --> 58:21.623
to keep our people safe again.

58:21.706 --> 58:22.916
(WIND WHOOSHING)

58:22.957 --> 58:25.752
YOUNG TANIEL: The children
circled the Western Wood,

58:25.835 --> 58:29.506
which had been the monster's
hunting ground for so long.

58:30.381 --> 58:33.593
And they buried
13 sacred shards.

58:33.635 --> 58:35.678
Deep into the earth.

58:35.762 --> 58:39.098
♪ (ETHEREAL CHORAL MUSIC
PLAYING) ♪

58:47.190 --> 58:49.943
YOUNG TANIEL:
Over each stone, they lit a fire

58:49.984 --> 58:51.819
to mark its place,

58:51.903 --> 58:55.156
a line The Galloo
could not cross.

58:58.952 --> 59:02.830
Our people made a sacred promise
to guard the pillars

59:02.914 --> 59:04.499
and keep their places secret.

59:06.251 --> 59:08.378
So that the monster
that's trapped inside

59:08.461 --> 59:10.755
could never break free.

59:12.632 --> 59:15.260
Our people would be safe,

59:15.301 --> 59:18.263
and The Galloo would remain
within these pillars...

59:19.556 --> 59:20.723
forever.

59:22.517 --> 59:25.019
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
-Well done, Taniel.

59:29.732 --> 59:30.942
Now, you're a part of--

59:30.984 --> 59:33.695
♪ (EERIE MUSIC PLAYING) ♪

59:34.821 --> 59:35.822
Auntie?

59:37.574 --> 59:39.534
(ECHOING RUMBLE)

59:40.702 --> 59:41.995
Are you okay?

59:42.078 --> 59:43.121
(BOOMING CLAP)

59:43.162 --> 59:47.000
-(HANDS CLAPPING)
-♪ (MUSIC TURNS OMINOUS) ♪

59:48.167 --> 59:49.586
Well done, Taniel.

59:50.336 --> 59:51.504
Great story.

59:52.171 --> 59:54.257
So, tell me, where are they now?

59:56.467 --> 59:57.594
The pillars.

59:58.303 --> 59:59.929
How do I find them?

01:00:02.181 --> 01:00:03.308
You can tell me.

01:00:07.186 --> 01:00:08.187
Come on.

01:00:18.031 --> 01:00:22.410
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

01:00:26.914 --> 01:00:29.208
(WIND HOWLING)

01:00:34.380 --> 01:00:35.381
Through there.

01:00:35.465 --> 01:00:37.800
♪ (MUSIC CONTINUES) ♪

01:00:41.763 --> 01:00:43.723
TANIEL: Follow the tunnels
under the old well...

01:00:46.142 --> 01:00:47.727
and you'll find the pillars.

01:00:47.810 --> 01:00:51.481
♪ (MUSIC TURNS SINISTER) ♪

01:00:52.649 --> 01:00:57.904
♪ (MUSIC BUILDS) ♪

01:00:57.945 --> 01:00:59.364
-(ECHOING RUMBLE)
-♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪

01:00:59.405 --> 01:01:03.076
♪ (CEREMONIAL DRUMS
BEATING RHYTHMICALLY) ♪

01:01:03.159 --> 01:01:09.332
♪ (SINGER SINGING
IN INDIGENOUS LANGUAGE) ♪

01:01:09.415 --> 01:01:15.254
♪ (GROUP SINGING
IN INDIGENOUS LANGUAGE) ♪

01:01:15.296 --> 01:01:20.927
♪ (DRUMS AND SINGING CONTINUE) ♪

01:01:33.606 --> 01:01:40.488
♪ (DRUMS AND SINGING CONTINUE) ♪

01:01:54.127 --> 01:01:56.045
♪ (DRUMS AND SINGING CONCLUDE) ♪
